post_text:
On Friday, Aug. 21, Greene Central School hosted its second Dairy and Produce Giveaway Day. The event took place at the Intermediate School bus loop and was hosted in collaboration with the SUNY Morrisville Norwich Campus, The Food Bank of Central New York, American Dairy Association North East, Chenango United Way, Rentals to Go, NYS Dept. of Agriculture and Markets, Norwich Beverage Corp., and Chobani.

During the event, 300 boxes of dairy products and produce were given away within two hours. Together, volunteers handed out:
· 3,000 ears of corn
· 1,014 quarts of yogurt
· 662 gallons of milk
· 600 cucumbers
· 600 bell peppers
· 384 quarts of sour cream
· 384 pounds of cheese
· 300 heads of lettuce
· 300 heads of cabbage
· 300 yellow squash
· 300 pints of grape tomatoes
· 300 pints of blueberries

Thank you to all the volunteers, businesses, and organizations that made this possible, and thank you to all the community members that came out.

Graduation Ceremony Announcement
Due to the heavy rains that are anticipated this morning, GCS will be delaying the Graduation Ceremony for 3 hours. Parking will begin at noon and the ceremony will begin at 1:00 PM. We apologize for any inconvenience, but we feel it is necessary in order to give our seniors the ceremony they deserve. A HUGE THANK YOU TO RAYMOND CORPORATION FOR THEIR SUPPORT IN ALLOWING THIS TO HAPPEN!

The technology and material drop off and student item pick up will run Tuesday, June 16 to Thursday, June 18. Tuesday's hours are from 8-2, Wednesday, from 3-6, and Thursday, from 8-2.
Students should bring all school materials. For example; Chromebooks (with chargers), calculators, textbooks, etc. during one of the aforementioned time slots. Students should return their technology and school materials to their specific buildings, which will also have supplies packaged and ready for them that they may have left at the school before closure.

post_text:
In years past, the Greene Teachers Association held a tea to honor its retiring faculty and staff. COVID-19 changed those plans this year so, instead, the GTA hosted a parade Friday, June 12, in honor of Meryt Allmendinger, Sue Funnell, Mary McBride, John Sininger and Nancy Swift, who will be retiring at the end of the school year.
Faculty and staff drove through the parking circle at the Intermediate and Primary schools, waving goodbye and wishing good luck to the five. Some gave the retirees going away gifts as well.

Greene Community Scholarship FUND
May 4 at 4:28 PM ·

SAVE THE DATE! The 15th annual Spring Slice Golf Tournament is planned this year for Saturday, June 13 at the Genegantslet Golf Course! As soon as we are given the all clear and know we can hold the tournament safely, we’ll be sending out the notices to our past participants. For anyone who hasn’t played before, it’s a fun time and the proceeds go to a great cause; scholarships for our graduating seniors. They’ve had a tough senior year so, come on out and support them. We’ll ALL be ready for golf by then. In the meantime, stay safe everyone!
For more information, or to reserve a spot, e-mail us: gcsf@stny.rr.com.

Here’s an update on our Thoughtexchange.

There are some great ideas in this exchange, and we need your help to make sure we understand what’s most important to you. If you’re game, please head back into the exchange and rate more thoughts.

Please use this link to jump back into the exchange and add stars to show how strongly you agree or disagree with this, and other thoughts.

https://my.thoughtexchange.com/733217726

The exchange will be open until 4:00pm on May 1st. Please take some time to participate before then.

The results of this Thoughtexchange will help us understand your concerns and what you see as opportunities around the District’s response to COVID-19 and overall communication procedures. Everyone’s voice matters, so your participation is crucial and valued.

Thank you and stay healthy!

post_text: Greene Central School will be joining the National Federation of State High Schools in a tribute to the class of 2020. They have asked schools all over the country to turn on their field lights at 8:20 (20:20 military time) for 20 min. and 20 sec. as a tribute to the class of 2020. This is in support of all the opportunities they have missed this year. We will turn on our stadium lights each weeknight at 8:20 in support of the GCS class of 2020. This is just one more inexpensive way the district can show our support for our graduating class.

text: The Greene Central School District will hold a special BOE meeting on Wednesday, March 18, 2020 at 5:30 PM. The meeting will be held to pass a resolution regarding employee payroll during the mandated school closure due to the coronavirus.

post_text:
GCS takes pride in providing free breakfast and lunch for students on a daily basis. We understand the importance of student nutrition and our food service team has created a plan to continue this service during our mandated school closure. Beginning Wednesday March 18th, we will begin providing a "grab & go" breakfast and lunch. Any student ages 18 and under can pick up these meals at the High School entrance from 11:00am-12:30pm, Monday-Friday until school re-opens. Any student that is not able to pick up food can have it delivered to their home daily from school staff.
Our staff has surveyed and called every family in the district to offer this service. If you were missed or at anytime decide you would like to participate, please call any of the school offices and sign up for this service 607-656-4161.

Chenango County has ordered the closing of schools effective WEDNESDAY, MARCH 18th. District officials and staff will be meeting this afternoon to finalize the district's plans moving forward. At the completion of the meeting the district will make an official statement of the plan moving forward. Tomorrow remains a conference day and we will update the community in a few hours on the finalized plan. Anything else posted on the internet not from GCS may not be accurate. Thank you again for your patience and understanding as we work through this unprecedented situation.
Tim Calice

The Music in Our Schools Concert will start early tonight at 6:30 p.m. Intermediate band and choral students, please report to the cafeteria at 6:00 p.m.
The Boys’ Basketball Sectional Semi-Final Game vs. Watkins Glen will also be played tonight at SUNY Cortland. Warm-ups are scheduled to begin at approximately 8:30 p.m.

We hope that by adjusting the start time of the concert, it will accommodate support of both student activities.
Best wishes to our students for successful events tonight.

post_text: Congratulations to the Boys Varsity Swim Team on a great performance at the Section IV Class C Final Meet. Trent deHaan came away as the Class C Champion in the 100 Freestyle, and runner-up in the 50 Freestyle. Luke DeJager took 4th place in the 100 Butterfly, and 9th place in the 200 Freestyle. Geoffrey Walker took 8th place in the 100 Butterfly, and 13th in the 200 IM. Ayden Doolittle took 14th in the 50 Freestyle & 16th in the 100 Backstroke. Dalton Krupp took 14th in the 500 Freestyle. Michael Giannetto took 15th in the 100 Freestyle. Cooper Klumpp took 14th place in the 100 Breaststroke. The 200 Medley Relay team of Doolittle, DeJager, deHaan, Walker took 4th place. The 200 Freestyle Relay team of Klumpp, Doolittle, Gianetto, & Krupp took 7th place. The 400 Freestyle Relay Team of Krupp, Walker, DeJager, & deHaan took 6th place. What a great way to end the season!

post_text: 2/18: ( JV Boys Basketball) Greene had the one two punch going on the offensive end at Unatego. Joey Gibbs hitting shots inside the paint and Dallas Roe dominating the low post as Greene rolled on to a 34-21 victory. The Greene boys had their best defensive effort of the season holding Unatego to 21 points. Greene ended up winning their last 10 games after starting the season 1-5. Congratulations to the JV Boys on an outstanding season. Greene ended up 11-5. Dallas Roe had 13 points and 10 rebounds. Joey Gibbs chipped in 12 points, 5 assists and 3 steals. Jakob Cook added 4 points and 2 assists. Jesse Ledford had 3 points and 2 assists. Grayson Flanagan contributed 2 points, 2 rebounds and 1 steal.

Greene out scored Unatego in the third quarter 12-3. Greene went on to win a low scoring game 35-28. Dallas Roe had 17 points and 5 rebounds. Liam Flanagan added 8 points and 4 rebounds. Jakob Cook chipped in 5 points and 3 assists. Joey Gibbs added 3 points and 6 assists. Jesse Ledford rounded out the scoring with 2 points, 3 assists, 1 steal and 1 blocked shot.

post_text: 2/11: JV Boys Basketball: Greene and Bainbridge-Guilford were tied after the first quarter 8-8. In the second quarter Joey Gibbs came off the bench and sparked the Trojans attack as Greene went on to out score Bainbridge-Guilford 19-5 to take a 27-13 lead into half time. Greene never looked back as they went on to win the game 48-37. Liam Flanagan had 13 points and 7 rebounds. Aiden Pickhard chipped in 12 points. Joey Gibbs contributed 11 points, 7 assists and 3 steals. Dallas Roe had 6 points and 6 rebounds. Jakob Cook added 4 points. Mike Swift chipped in 2 points.

post_text: 2/12: The varsity girls’ basketball team defeated BG on senior night by a score of 56-20 to finish the regular season 12-6. Every girl on the team scored, led by Emma Smith’s 16 points and Olivia Kennedy’s 11. The team had 16 assists, with Madison Rice picking up 4 to go with her season best 6 points. The team picked up 10 steals, led by Kylee Peck’s three, while only having 7 turnovers. The team will next play against D/H in the MAC playoffs on Monday night in Deposit.
